 Stoicism and Epicureanism, to write poems that reflect on how to live a thoughtful and moderate life amid mindless over-consumption, how to achieve and maintain true love and friendship, and how to face disaster and death with patience and courage. From memorable counsel on the pointlessness of worrying about the future to valuable advice about living in the moment, these poems, by the man who famously advised us to carpe diem or “harvest the day,” continue to provide brilliant meditations on perennial human problems.Featuring translations of, and commentary on, complete poems from Horace’s Odes, Satires, Epistles, and Epodes, accompanied by the original Latin, How to Be Content is both an ideal introduction to Horace and a compelling book of timeless wisdom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAugustinian.  aAugustus.  aEpicurean.  aHorace biography.  aHorace commentary.  aHorace in context.  aHorace poetry selection.  aHorace.  aHoratian.  aRoman lyric poet.  aStoic.  aannotated Horace poems.  abiographical context.  acommentaries.  ahappiness.  ahistorical context.  ahow to be happy.  ahow to live.  aideas.  ainterpretations.  alife advice.  aliterary criticism.  ameaning of Horace poems.  ameaning of Horace poetry.  anew Horace translation.  aphilosophy.  aseize the day.  aselected Horace poems.  athought.1 aHarrison, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is